{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17507245","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17507245"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:51:00+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:51:00+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2614"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2614","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2614"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.12,0.5,0.1,0.07,0.22]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2614"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112941"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2614","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2614"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2614"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94973"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"354"},{"type":"tags","id":"1094"},{"type":"tags","id":"1114"},{"type":"tags","id":"3424"},{"type":"tags","id":"9339"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2876"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2878"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27072"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45506"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112941","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/112941"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 40-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a several-month history of dull, burning, retrosternal chest pain after meals. He finds it difficult to lie down for a few hours after eating due to the pain. He also describes an eight-year history of dysphagia to both solids and liquids, which has progressed to occasional regurgitation of undigested food over the last three years, worsening recently. He has not noticed any abdominal pain, changes in bowel motions, or weight loss. His medical history includes well-controlled hypertension, for which he takes ramipril. He does not smoke or drink alcohol. On examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. A barium swallow study is ordered (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Botulinum toxin injection","Cardiomyotomy with fundoplication","Oesophageal stent placement","Oesophagectomy","Pneumatic dilatation"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EAchalasia is a primary oesophageal motility disorder characterised by the failure of the lower oesophageal sphincter to relax and the absence of peristalsis in the body of the oesophagus. This leads to the classic symptoms of dysphagia to both solids and liquids, regurgitation of undigested food, and retrosternal chest pain.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has long-standing symptoms and radiological evidence of severe, end-stage achalasia with significant oesophageal dilatation. Current guidelines recommend \u003Cstrong\u003Ecardiomyotomy with fundoplication\u003C/strong\u003E for patients with severe achalasia who are fit for surgery. A cardiomyotomy (Heller myotomy) involves incising the muscle of the lower oesophageal sphincter to relieve the obstruction. Adding a fundoplication (an anti-reflux procedure) is recommended to prevent gastro-oesophageal reflux, which is a common complication of the myotomy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBotulinum toxin injection\u003C/strong\u003E into the lower oesophageal sphincter is a less invasive treatment option, but its effects are temporary, typically lasting only six to 12 months. It is generally reserved for patients who are not suitable candidates for more definitive surgical or endoscopic interventions. Given this patient is young and otherwise well, a more durable solution is preferable.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPneumatic dilatation\u003C/strong\u003E is an effective endoscopic treatment for achalasia, involving forceful dilatation of the lower oesophageal sphincter with a balloon. While it is a valid initial treatment, its efficacy is lower in patients with a severely dilated oesophagus, as seen in this case. Surgical myotomy generally provides better long-term outcomes in this patient group.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOesophageal stent placement\u003C/strong\u003E is not a standard treatment for achalasia. Stents are typically used for malignant strictures or perforations and are not recommended for benign motility disorders like achalasia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOesophagectomy\u003C/strong\u003E is a major operation involving the removal of the oesophagus. It is reserved for patients with end-stage, \u0027sigmoid\u0027 oesophagus who have failed other interventions like cardiomyotomy or pneumatic dilatation, or in cases where there is a concern for malignancy. While this patient may eventually require this procedure, it is not the initial definitive treatment.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Achalasia is a motility disorder of the oesophagus characterised by impaired relaxation of the lower oesophageal sphincter and loss of peristalsis in the oesophageal body.","Patients with severe achalasia require definitive treatment with a cardiomyotomy.","Fundoplication is recommended concurrently with cardiomyotomy to reduce distal oesophageal acid exposure."],"references":["Vaezi MF, Pandolfino JE, Yadlapati RH, Greer KB, Kavitt RT. ACG Clinical Guidelines: Diagnosis and Management of Achalasia. Am J Gastroenterol. 2020 Sep;115(9):1393-1411. doi: 10.14309/ajg.0000000000000731. PMID: 32773454 Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/32773454/","Mayo D, Griffiths EA, Khan OA, Szymankiewicz MA, Wakefield CW, Thompson SK. Does the addition of a fundoplication improve outcomes for patients undergoing laparoscopic Heller\u0027s cardiomyotomy? Int J Surg. 2012;10(6):301-4. doi: 10.1016/j.ijsu.2012.04.002. Epub 2012 Apr 14. PMID: 22510440. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/22510440/","Midya S, Ghosh D, Mahmalat MW. Fundoplication in laparoscopic Heller\u0027s cardiomyotomy for achalasia. Cochrane Database Syst Rev. 2022 Dec 8;12(12):CD013386. doi: 10.1002/14651858.CD013386.pub2. PMID: 36478353; PMCID: PMC9730445. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/36478353/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94973"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2614"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"15289"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"15289","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/15289"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/815c71e3-196f-4bb8-8f81-fd10cf754a8a.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/815c71e3-196f-4bb8-8f81-fd10cf754a8a.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":1362,"height":1192}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94973","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/94973"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-08T14:54:35+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-08T14:57:28+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2614"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112941"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"ty